In article <1992May27.155853.13497@msuinfo.cl.msu.edu> mrr@scss3.cl.msu.edu (Mark Riordan) writes:
>Here's a concrete example, sample output from a program under development:
>
>User: fictitious@node.domain
>PublicKeyInfo:
> MFowCgYEVQgBAQICAgsDTAAwSQJCBZjdie62Fwv0s9+4Um5tirw4FsHdyrLaU0eL
> g2vLpKKw/R8p2X0r9VYpcNpLOQi9tJv7UMUU2u54FVwZMLKdSqnTAgMBAAF=
>


I realize that code groups are not part of the machine-readable standard,
but for humans, and especially for transcription into a computer,

MFowC gYEVQ gBAQI CAgsD TAAwS QJCBZ jdie6 2Fwv0 s9+4U m5tir w4FsH
dyrLa U0eLg 2vLpK Kw/R8 p2X0r 9VYpc NpLOQ i9tJv 7UMUU 2u54F VwZML
KdSqn TAgMB AAF=

is a lot more manageable.  Meanwhile, I would suggest that check bytes be
added (maybe every 5 code groups) so that in case of transcription error,
the error can be localized.  ECC might help as well.
